Public procurement of works and prevention of corruption
Joint report of the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
The award of services by contracting authorities is of great importance both for the state and for the economy.
The task of the State is to use public funds as economically and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure that competition is broadly unlimited across borders, contracting authorities must comply with EU guidelines when it comes to awarding them from certain value limits (thresholds).
For this purpose, EU member states must transfer and apply EU procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.
The award of services is also a vulnerable area.
In view of the generally high potential for damage, contracting authorities must therefore implement appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue benefits in the award of their contracts.
In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits both for the allocation of works across the EU and for the prevention of corruption.
The main focus of the audits was the application of EU procurement law transposed into national legislation, as well as the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in construction and road construction and transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU thresholds were also included in the considerations with a view to preventing corruption.
The audit results of both Court of Auditors are summarised in this Joint Report.
The report should also be addressed to international institutions, such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
Examination areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Audit Court on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional tests carried out by the construction administrations in 2011/2012, which are responsible for the federal road construction and construction of the federal government in Germany.
He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and major building projects.
In addition, the Federal Court of Auditors drew on results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from the years 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction measures in road construction, rail infrastructure construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the public procurement of the federal government is mainly carried out by the construction administrations of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Construction Administration is centrally responsible for public transport infrastructure awards.
In the construction sector, the awards are carried out decentralised by those bodies that use state budget resources.
In both countries, freelancers are also involved in sub-sectors of procurement procedures.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.
Development of procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procedures limited to the national field are governed by budgetary law and the administrative rules based on it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national awards, many supplementary individual schemes are provided by internal administrative provisions.
such as the so-called “Vergabehandbücher” of the Federal Government, in which the statutory requirements are supplemented or further formulated in accordance with the law of public procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Procurement Act and other statutory provisions applicable both above and below the EU thresholds.
Public procurement law was substantially amended in 2012.
The new regulation strengthened transparency in the use of public funds, allowed greater competition and limited the possibilities for corruption in the procurement procedure.
Broad lines of procurement law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiated procedure shall apply in particular to EU-wide awards.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold apply the national types of procurement (public tender, limited tender, hands-free award), but which largely correspond to the aforementioned EU-wide types of procurement.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of prioritisation of the open procedure (in the case of procurement to be carried out throughout the EU) and the public tender (in the case of national procurement).
In the open procedure and in the public tender procedure, any interested company may submit a tender.
Another key feature of German procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized enterprises.
In particular, the division of a total construction measure into specialist and partial batches is used for this purpose.
The individual allocation of these lots is intended to allow as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the aforementioned features of German procurement law are proven tools for achieving economic results.
More than 330,000 construction companies employing 1.9 million employees are active in Germany.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable for construction projects below the EU threshold.
An exception is the simplified procedure, which allows a less stringent procedure to be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law contains provisions in accordance with EU law that require contracts to be concluded if competition is guaranteed and an advantageous price is achieved.
Current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow contracting entities to choose between open and non-open procedures.
In the Czech Republic there are over 85,000 construction companies, of which about 1,900 companies employing 20 or more employees.
