Summary of the results of parallel tests
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries on the allocation of works across the EU and on the prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of both Court of Auditors compared the corresponding legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, particularly in the areas of building construction and road construction.
In doing so, they essentially noted:
The EU directives on the award of works by contracting authorities have been transposed into national law both in the Czech Republic and in Germany (Nos 1 and 3.1).
In addition to EU requirements, the prevention of corruption is also served by the procurement rules of both countries, which differ in their focus and in their detail (point 3.2).
In both countries, an essential requirement for the procurement documents is that they must contain all the information required for an appropriate tender.
The specifications must be neutral and must not contain restrictions on competition.
In Germany, the procurement documents have largely met these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it remains a problem to adequately determine the subject-matter of the contract.
In Germany, construction works must be divided into lots as far as possible in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the Federal Republic of Germany, this requirement was largely implemented.
In its tests, in particular in the field of road construction, the NKÚ found that the award of large services without lots or with very large lots could affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.
Constraints in the market potential can lead to significant cost increases and pose the risk of price or other agreements.
Pursuant to the provisions of both countries, the contracting entities may, under certain conditions, agree, in principle, with the undertakings already commissioned, additional or modified services which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (point 4.1).
The respective requirements for determining the type of award were predominantly followed in both countries.
Under the rules of the Czech Republic, contracting entities are free to choose between open and non-open procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary priority of the open procedure applies to EU-wide procurement or public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national procurement.
This allows more companies to submit offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, makes it difficult to find prices between bidders and leads to the most economical results.
In the case of construction projects whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited construction administrations generally awarded the construction services throughout Europe.
The correct estimation of the estimated value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of award.
In Germany, cost databases are used to investigate costs for public buildings, especially in building construction.
based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective instrument (point 4.2).
In the case of works to be awarded throughout Europe, preliminary information and notices must be published. This is intended to strengthen competition by allowing interested companies to adapt to the aforementioned awards at an early stage.
As a rule, the audited construction administrations adhered to this requirement.
In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or lack of controls may affect competition (point 4.3).
The selection of candidates to participate in non-public procurement procedures is particularly vulnerable to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of invited candidates must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be disclosed beforehand.
In addition to EU requirements, contracting agencies in both countries should switch as often as possible among the companies to be requested when selecting candidates.
In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are some very detailed specifications in Germany.
In some cases, the audited administrations did not take these requirements into account.
In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).
In both countries, it is necessary to ensure that the interested parties receive the same information during the tender phase in order to ensure that competition is equal to opportunities.
Contact between these companies and with freelancers involved in the drafting of the SOW shall be prevented as far as possible in order to avoid anti-competitive agreements.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
The audited construction administrations in Germany partly did not comply with these requirements (No. 4.5).
In opening up tenders, in particular, the multieye principle and the transparency principle must be observed in both countries.
The specifications for the labelling, documentation, safekeeping and confidentiality of the offers are intended to narrow the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.
The examinations in both countries showed only a few complaints (point 4.6).
Examination and evaluation of the tenders are defined in both countries by means of specifications for the organisation of structures and processes.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.
For example, contracting entities handed over tenders to third parties for examination without first looking through the tenders and sufficiently documenting abnormalities.
As a result, the offers were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulations (No. 4.7).
When concluding the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies participating in the competition will be informed of the proposed contract before the award of the contract.
This legal protection option also has a preventive function against corruptive behaviour.
The Czech Republic also provides for judicial review for non-EU procurement procedures.
Only in a few cases the contracting entities did not comply with the prescribed deadlines in the award of contracts or did not give way to the tenderers' tenders' content (point 4.8).
Documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible at the audited construction administrations in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the award notes of some procedures.
Some of the identified shortcomings also reduced the corruption prevention function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries largely met their reporting and reporting obligations (point 4.9).
Fundamentals of EU procurement law and prevention of corruption
EU Public Procurement Law
In order to ensure unlimited competition in the free movement of services and goods within the European Union, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, the Directives on Procurement Coordinating and Appeals, which were to be transposed into national law by the Member States.
The general procurement principles of the European Union are, in particular, that of competition, the requirement for equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination and the requirement of transparency.
In order to enforce these objectives, the procurement coordination directive contains specific rules for construction works to be awarded across the EU.
For this purpose, their estimated order amounts must reach or exceed the current amount of EUR 5,000,000.
The rules concern, in particular, the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the compliance with deadlines, including the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements which may be imposed on the qualification of candidates and the Appeal Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.
In the event of possible infringements of public procurement law, companies concerned may have the decisions of contracting authorities reviewed in review procedures.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives into national law.
Corruption prevention
Importance of the prevention of corruption
In both countries there is no legal definition of the term of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a trust to the private advantage.
which is normally initiated by the beneficiaries of those decisions.
Corruption can impede competition and result in significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of world economic performance.
For the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair conduct may call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of contracting authorities.
In doing so, they have to check the organisation of their administrations for areas that are particularly vulnerable to corruption in order to make appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the susceptibility of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly vulnerable area of work.
Measures to prevent corruption
In Germany, corruption — in particular bribery and bribery, as well as acceptance and authorization — is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a directive and recommendations on the prevention of corruption in the Federal Administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following basic principles have to be observed for the procurement sector: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eye principle and transparency, basic separation of planning, award and settlement, precise and complete documentation of the procurement procedures.
In addition, other anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into the procurement law regulations.
For example, in 2011, the responsible Federal Ministry for Proceeds in the Federal Highway Area introduced an electronically supported control system:
with which procurement data — such as the estimated costs and contract sums — as well as information on the involved freelancers are collected across the board and evaluated for abnormalities.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted by criminal and labour law.
The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of tenderers, as well as the prohibition of any discrimination, form the main basis of the prevention of corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has established anti-corruption measures in a anti-corruption strategy paper for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated it for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended therein have already been incorporated into national public procurement law and related administrative provisions.
The new legislation essentially includes the following rules: reduction of thresholds for smaller contracts, obligatory prior announcement of the award by the contracting party, including the reasons for the tendering procedure, prohibition of restricting the number of tenderers in non-open procedures and thus abolition of the number of tenderers. Possibility of selection of tenderers by lot procedure, introduction of the obligation to publish the procurement documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Results of the examination of the various stages of the award procedure
Procurement documents
Procurement documents The procurement documents shall contain all the information that tenderers need for a proper tender.
In particular, the procurement documents must allow for a correct calculation.
In doing so, the bidders shall not be transferred to any risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The procurement documents consist in particular of the specifications and the terms and conditions of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualifications (suitability) of the tenderers and the criteria that are relevant to the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law on procurement documents are in particular addressed to the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all tenderers and should restrict competition as little as possible.
The SOW must in principle be product-neutral.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the SOW is only permitted under strict conditions.
Avoiding restrictive requirements in the procurement documents is also an elementary principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the procurement documents must be avoided, since they provide scope for speculation in the compilation of tenders and for manipulation in their evaluation.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar regulations In both countries, EU technical specifications are transposed into national law.
The services are generally product-neutral without any manufacturer specifications.
In the service descriptions, the individual services must normally be subdivided into service units with respective quantities.
The prices must be agreed on on the basis of performance units (e.g. Euro per m ² or per unit).
Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by functional targets.
The specifications of the service shall in any case be complete and unambiguous.
They shall contain precise quantities and shall not include services which do not determine whether they are needed.
Compensation based on lump sums or time expenditure must be avoided as far as possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indefinite specifications in the procurement documents.
The specifications must enable tenderers to prepare their tenders safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The invitation to tender shall not be published until the procurement documents have been completed.
Differing regulations
There is no obligation to tender works in lots in the Czech Republic.
Where it is possible by type of service to be recovered, public contracting entities may divide works into several lots.
In Germany, construction works must be divided into lots, separately according to the quantity (partial lots) and/or by type or subject matter (skilled lots).
The aim is to enable SMEs to participate in the competition, increase the number of potential providers and make price arrangements more difficult.
This type of award is considered to be the most economical.
Evaluation criteria must be specified in the procurement documents in the Czech Republic, both in the EU-wide and in the national procedures.
This is intended to be fully and conclusively identifiable for applicants the criteria according to which their offers are to be evaluated.
In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the procurement documents, is only required for the EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria shall only be recorded in an administrative award note.
Procurement documents drawn up by contracted freelancers may not contain any references to these offices or involved planners or appraisers in Germany.
This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other unacceptable competitive advantages without the client's knowledge of contact with these freelancers.
This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send procurement documents or interpret planning documents for inspection.
The contact person of the companies is the client alone.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.
Additional or modified services that prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (additions) are almost always incurred in large construction projects.
In both countries, the statutory provisions allow, to a certain extent, the awarding of supplements to the already commissioned company without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary services may not exceed half of the main order.
In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies to such award without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the already ongoing construction work.
If additional services are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is generally not possible under the regulations in Germany.
In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the order already placed must be based on the price.
In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, small quantities cannot be offset against additional supplements.
Significant test results
BHR
Technical specifications and product-neutral tender
In individual cases, the specifications contained references to national technical approvals or standards which had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.
Some specifications also included product-related specifications — such as graffiti protection, grout tapes or noise protection panels — without this being required.
In some cases, performance requirements were described so accurately that only one product could be considered.
Tables of services broken down by subperformance
In any of the proceedings under consideration, the BRH has not found any breach of the requirement to write out services in a list of services broken down by partial services.
Completeness of the specifications
In the vast majority of procedures, the procurement documents were completed before the start of the invitations to tender.
In some cases, the procurement documents had to be corrected during the tendering phase because some positions or deadlines had changed.
In some cases, the tables of services contained items where they were not determined whether they were needed.
In fact, almost half of a list of services for demolition work consisted of such demand items.
Lots and evaluation criteria
Many awards lacked the stipulated justification for the reasons why the services advertised mainly according to professional lots were not further divided into partial lots.
There were no complaints when specifying the criteria to be used in the evaluation of tenders.
Information on freelancers
A small part of the specifications contained references to the involved freelancers.
Their names were partly on the cover pages or in attached plans or opinions.
In one case, the contracting party even explicitly asked the applicants to contact the architect “on questions of the call for tender”.
In the construction sector, in particular, the contracting entities attributed the complaints reported mainly to the omissions of the freelancers commissioned to draw up the specifications.
The construction services referred to the lack of capacity in order to be able to adequately monitor the specifications.
