Completeness of the specifications
During the construction of a motorway bypass, the specifications of services were changed four times in the context of a non-open procedure during the period August to September 2009;
since the scope of services increased substantially and the technical requirements had changed.
Tendering documents for social buildings contained inaccurate location information, insufficient structural preliminary investigations and incomplete design drawings, which had to be commissioned additional services.
When building a large library building, the specifications of the interior design did not contain any requirements for product quality.
As a result of these missing specifications, some subcontractors installed overpriced and unreasonably high quality equipment.
Lots and eligibility criteria
In the Czech Republic, the division of construction projects into partial lots or the award of partial contracts is not obligatory.
An examination of the three major sections of the construction of a motorway ring showed that a separate allocation of selected parts would have resulted in savings of up to EUR 31.6 million with a total cost of EUR 620.3 million.
For example, six different structures which were the subject of a single contract could have saved 2.5 million euros (25%) if they were awarded separately.
A separate allocation of 20 bridges would have made savings of 11.5 million euros (25%) compared to a total award.
When awarding construction services in road construction, the central contracting entity specified very extensive reference requirements as suitability criteria.
In the construction of a part of a motorway, the contracting body required the tenderers, in an open procedure, for example, to provide proof of at least three road construction projects worth EUR 28 million each from the last five years.
In the Czech Republic, a maximum of nine suppliers met these requirements.
The public procurement of another section of a motorway included six separate construction projects in which the contracting authority had specified an annual construction volume of at least EUR 480 million in the last three years as a qualifying criterion for the undertakings.
Two thirds of the funds allocated to road construction projects in 2008 and 2009 (i.e. EUR 2.5 billion out of a total of EUR 3.7 billion) were commissioned by a total of five companies carrying out the contracts alone or as a working group.
In 46 procurement procedures with a volume of EUR 528 million, only two or even one tenderer submitted a tender.
The NKÚ showed that a narrowing of market potential could lead to significant cost increases.
Additional services
In the construction of a motorway bypass, the contracting agency did not apply any of the procedures prescribed by law in the award of additional services in two cases and did not conclude any written contracts for the additional services.
Due to ambiguous volume and quality requirements, supplements were created in the first case of up to EUR 63.7 million (net) and in the second case up to EUR 165.4 million (net), thereby increasing the respective order volume by 21% and 91% respectively.
