Other findings
Based on a sampling of construction projects, the NKÚ found that the average cost of building a four-lane motorway in the Czech Republic is up to 14.6 million euros.
In Germany, on the other hand, according to an evaluation of long-term data by the Federal Ministry of Construction, the average cost of a four-lane motorway kilometre is up to 10.4 million euros.
This comparison suggests that motorway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take into account the EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition as well as the prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement for sufficient determination of the specifications should enable tenderers to correctly calculate and prepare their tenders,
protect the client from additional services to be agreed subsequently and also limit speculation margin.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for procurement documents are supplemented by regulations aimed at further reducing competition restrictions and manipulation possibilities.
In the Czech Republic there are no requirements to this extent, but transparency is increased by publishing the evaluation criteria for non-EU-wide procurement procedures.
The requirements for the SOW have been largely complied with in both countries.
However, in some cases, discrepancies had to be objected, which may also have led to restrictions on competition.
The requirement for the formation of lots in Germany promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the audit findings of the NKÚ, the award of large services without lots or with very large lots may result in restrictions on the field of suppliers to only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements in the Czech Republic in road construction have led to public contracts being awarded only to a narrow circle of suppliers and not allowing small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition.
Also, a limited number of competitors often leads to higher prices and increases the risk of price or other arrangements.
In the award and remuneration of additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches differ in both countries.
According to the EU requirements and the German regulations, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract can be awarded under certain conditions without procurement procedures with public notice.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20%, up to which additional services can be awarded to the original contractor in the negotiated procedure without notice.
