Determine the type of award and take into account the EU threshold
By defining the type of award, the contracting entity shall determine the extent of the number of undertakings participating in the competition.
It may leave the range of potential candidates and tenderers, for example by choosing an open procedure, to a large extent unlimited or limit the scope of non-public procurement procedures.
Europe-wide procurement procedures shall apply to construction projects that meet or exceed a threshold set by the EU.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
When choosing the type of award, the contracting authority shall take into account, in particular, the requirements for competition and transparency under European law.
If the estimated total contract value of the works of a project is equal to or above the EU threshold of currently EUR 5 million, the works must be awarded throughout Europe according to open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
The contracting authority may, in the case of construction projects reaching or exceeding the EU threshold, derogate to the principle of Europe-wide procurement and award works in national procurement procedures provided that the estimated contract value of the respective lot is less than EUR 1,000,000 and the sum of these lots is 20 % of the estimated total contract value of all works contracts.
A uniform construction project must not be divided into individual measures without imperative reasons or deliberately estimated at too low cost values in order to remove it from the obligation to allocate construction services throughout Europe.
Since restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the type of award is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed justification of the chosen award method and the examination of the application of EU procurement rules are important elements of the documentation of the procurement procedure.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed EU legislation on procurement procedures and the threshold value into national law.
Differing regulations
The Czech Republic has also transferred the principle of equality of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU Directive to its construction contractions which are not subject to the EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the non-open procedure, without the decision being to be docued or justified. However, other procedures are only possible under certain conditions defined by law.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or, in the case of national procurement, the public invitation to tender takes priority. This is defined by budgetary and public procurement law, as well as by the directives on the prevention of corruption.
Other types of procurement — such as the non-open procedure or the restricted invitation to tender — are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finalised in public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be substantiated and documented in a comprehensible manner.
The principle of prioritisation of the open procedure or the public invitation to tender is intended to ensure that competition is as unlimited as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by setting on specific tenderers and to make possible price arrangements between tenderers more difficult.
The principle of public tender is a key element in the prevention of corruption in Germany.
The correct estimation of the estimated value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of award.
The construction services in Germany can use planning and cost databases of public administrations and other organisations to determine the estimated costs in the area of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost parameters for building categories, usage units, components or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost metrics, the estimated contract value of a planned project or construction work to be awarded can be determined.
Appropriate cost databases for road construction in Germany have only some construction administrations.
However, a nationwide introduction is envisaged for all road construction administrations.
Contracting entities in the Czech Republic cannot rely on central databases or average price inquiries of comparable construction measures to determine the estimated cost of works.
In most cases, cost investigations are based on estimates of the financing body or are based on the amount of funds made available to the construction service.
Measures to standardize cost investigation procedures are still in the early stages.
In the context of the anti-corruption plan for 2011 - 2012, the relevant ministries were commissioned to create a database of standardized building materials and materials.
