Main test results BRH
Choice of the award procedure
The audited contracting entities broadly wrote out the works in an open procedure or in a public tender procedure, thus following the budgetary and public procurement requirements.
In 2011, 59.5% of the federal construction services in the construction sector were tendered publicly or in open proceedings.
In road construction, this share was 94.8%.
The choice of non-public procurement types lacked some detailed justifications as to why the contracting entities had to deviate from the open procedure or the public tender principle.
In a cross-sectional investigation, the BRH found on the basis of more than 16,000 procurement procedures that non-public procurement types have significant disadvantages in competition compared to open procedures and public tenders and increase the risk of tampering and corruption.
In building construction, more than twice as many tenders were submitted in public tenders as in restricted tenders and nearly three times as many tenders as for freehand tenders.
The investigation also showed that tenders prices for restricted tenders and freehand tenders were on average 6% and 10% higher than for public tenders.
Parallel investigations by the Federal Ministry of Construction and a State Auditing Court confirmed the profitability differences between public and non-public procurement types.
As a result of its investigations into economic efficiency, the Federal Ministry of Construction even found doubled differences between public and non-public procurement procedures.
Take into account the EU threshold
As a rule, the contracting entities audited drawn up procurement plans for the construction projects for which they had determined an estimated total contract amount of more than EUR 5 million, in which they set out the works to be awarded by EU wide and national procurement procedures.
According to the procurement plans, a share of more than 80% of the works throughout the EU has always been allocated.
It was not possible to circumvent the obligation to allowances across the EU due to low estimates.
However, in part due to incorrect calculations, there was actually less than the minimum proportion of EUwide procurement procedures.
During construction, some contracting entities inadvertently changed the specifications of their procurement plans.
They did not justify these changes and did not demonstrate that the minimum proportion of EU-wide procurement procedures continued to be respected.
For most of the construction measures under review, the proportion of EU-wide procurement was usually lower than the allocation plan according to the settlement results.
In some cases, for projects above the EU threshold, contracting entities violated the requirement to tender all EUR 1,000,000 and more single lots in EU-wide procedures.
