Selection of candidates for non-public award types
In contrast to public procurement procedures, in the case of non-public procurement procedures, not every undertaking interested in the performance of the services to be awarded can participate in the competition.
In the case of non-public procurement procedures, the contracting entity must first make a selection of which companies are to be invited to tender.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption EU rules allow a limitation of the number of applicants for EU-wide non-public procurement procedures.
However, in the case of non-open procedures, at least five companies must be invited to tender.
A minimum of three companies shall be invited in negotiated procedures with a notice of award.
In any case, the number of invited candidates must be sufficiently high to ensure real competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not lead to discrimination and must be disclosed beforehand.
The selection of undertakings to be requested is a process within the procurement procedure that is highly vulnerable to manipulation, for example by allowing certain undertakings to be unilaterally preferred.
In addition, restricting competition to a few companies also favours possible collusion of candidates.
In both cases, the contract result may be significantly impaired at the expense of the client.
Contracting entities must therefore take special measures against possible manipulations, carry out adequate controls and, in particular, ensure the transparency and traceability of this procedural step.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar rules
The rules for selecting candidates are similar in both countries.
In addition to the EU requirements, the contracting entities should switch as often as possible among the companies to be requested when selecting candidates.
Nor should competition be limited to companies located in certain regions.
The contracting authorities shall justify the selection of candidates and document the course of the competition in their award notes.
Differing regulations
In Germany, at least three suitable candidates must be invited to tender for limited tenders and in the case of freehand tenders, in principle, several suitable candidates must be invited to submit tenders.
Under the new Czech rules, with the exception of two special areas, it is inadmissible to restrict the number of tenderers in the case of non-open procedures and negotiated procedures.
In Germany, the multi-eye principle must be observed when selecting companies.
For example, if an employee has proposed a number of companies for a non-public procurement procedure, the management level of the construction service or a representative from the contracting authority must, as a rule, amend this proposal by removing a proposed undertaking and/or supplementing a new undertaking.
The aim is to prevent a single person from finally determining the circle of undertakings to participate in the competition.
Otherwise, in the case of manipulative intentions, this could allow far-reaching arrangements among the parties involved.
The list of companies to be requested must be kept confidential, including to freelancers, and should not be made publicly available.
