Examination and evaluation of offers
Examination and evaluation of tenders The client must review and evaluate the tenders present at the opening date.
It shall determine the tender for the award of the award which best meets the requirements according to the given award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
The EU guidelines provide for a multi-stage procedure:
Firstly, the suitability of the tenderers should be determined.
Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
In principle, undertakings which are convicted by law for bribery or fraud should be excluded from participation in the procurement procedure.
The tenders of the non-excluded tenderers shall be constructed, technically and economically assessed and assessed on the basis of the award criteria previously announced.
The client shall determine the most economically advantageous tender. Offers with unusually low prices are to be examined in particular by the client.
The examination and evaluation of tenders is a particularly vulnerable phase of the procurement procedure.
For example, bidders can be excluded unjustifiably or tenders that do not meet the requirements can be kept in competition.
Preferring or disadvantaging bidders may inadvertently affect the value result and thus prevent the finding of the most economically advantageous offer.
The contracting authority must therefore take special measures to ensure that the persons responsible for the audit and evaluation meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and decisions taken.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar rules
In accordance with the requirements of the EU, offers in both countries must be examined and evaluated in multi-stage procedures.
The requirements for the proof of suitability of undertakings to be submitted and the award criteria to be taken into account in the evaluation and their weighting are laid down in the notices or the award documents and cannot be changed during the procedure.
After the bidding event has been checked, the eligibility criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of the tenders.
The evaluation must be limited to the award criteria.
The tenders submitted must first be formally examined immediately to determine whether they are complete and, for example, contain abnormalities that could indicate possible manipulation intentions.
If bidders are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their tenders, they shall be informed thereof without delay.
If the evaluation of the tenders reveals an unreasonably low price, the tenderer must be given the opportunity to comment before any possible exclusion of his offer.
The decisions taken during the review and evaluation of the offers must be clearly documented.
Differing regulations
In Germany, tenders to be kept secret may only be made available to persons directly responsible for processing.
The review of the tenders and the computational verification of the tenders may only be carried out by the prospecting firm.
It shall only employ staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The exercise of further auditing and evaluation tasks is not further regulated.
If freelancers are entrusted with the examination and evaluation, they must treat the tenders confidentially.
They may only make proposals for decisions to be taken by the contracting authorities.
In the Czech Republic, contracting committees must be formed to examine and assess tenders.
The committees draw up evaluation reports with proposals for award.
As in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the award of contracts.
If evidence or declarations required for submission of tenders is submitted incomplete in Germany, the issuing party shall give tenderers the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the deadline can the offer be excluded from the evaluation.
In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the issuing company whether it gives tenderers the opportunity to complete missing evidence or explanations.
If a bidder fails to do so, he must be excluded.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the unit prices (prices for partial services) of the offers must be examined.
Where the price structure of the offer reveals that partial performance prices are too low or too high, the tenderer shall be encouraged to address those ambiguity.
If he fails to do so and the procuring person can provide proof of a mixed costing of the prices, this offer must be excluded.
This is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant changes in quantities in partial services when calculating their offer, which can lead to significant cost increases in construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is valued, but not the appropriateness of the prices for partial services.
A mixed costing cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
Tenders with unreasonably high or low prices may not be awarded in Germany.
Where one or more tenders are less than the correct price determination of the contracting entity or the total tenderers' bid amounts by 10% or more, tenderers shall prove that their tenders are correctly calculated.
If they are unable to do so, the issuing authority may exclude the tenders in question.
In the Czech Republic, the invitation to tender may be cancelled after the economic viability assessment if only tenders with unreasonably low prices are available.
Contrary to German public procurement law, the contract cannot be refused for tenders with prices substantially higher than the client's calculation.
If there is a suspicion of restrictive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority shall immediately report to its specialist supervisory level.
The latter has to decide what measures to be taken and whether the antitrust authority or the public prosecutor's office should be informed.
For example, the supervisory level must also agree with works of more than 50,000 euros, if a contract is to be awarded freehand, if the tender is not to be awarded on the tender with the lowest price or if the tender is to be cancelled.
There are no corresponding regulations in the Czech Republic.
