As a result, it remained unclear whether the estimated estimate was excessive or the offer price was too low.
Later, the client assessed the commissioned company as a “low-cost company” which could not keep quality or deadlines.
In another invitation to tender, a construction service contracted a tender whose price was 35% higher than the value of the cost calculation.
It did not terminate the call for tenders and stated the non-material justification that this company could conclude on a satisfactory calculation.
Suspicion of irregularities
In the case of an audited construction administration, there were two cases of irregularities, both of which were reported to the technical inspectorate.
In one of the cases, the calculation of two tenderers was identical in the case of an invitation to tender, so that the contractors excluded both tenders from the procedure.
In the application of the other regulations, the examinations did not show any material objections.
NKÚ
qualifying
The contracting authorities did not exclude tenderers from the procedure for many of the projects under examination, including higher education, road construction and the extension of the rail network, although they did not meet the requirements specified in the tender documents or could not prove their suitability to the required extent. On the other hand, in one case, a contractors could not prove or explain why it had excluded a tenderer that had met the requirements.
Rating
When awarding works for a water treatment plant, the contracting contractor did not take into account the specified evaluation criteria in the examination and evaluation of tenders.
In the case of a construction project for the expansion of the railway network, the contracting body determined the weighting of the evaluation criteria only at the beginning of the evaluation.
In the case of road conservation measures, the predetermined criterion “shortening the construction phase” was misjudged in one procedure.
As a result, the reduction offered was not sufficiently taken into account in the second and third tenderers.
Documentation of the selection of quotes
In the case of three procurement procedures under housing promotion, the contracting entity did not document the criteria it applied and the basis on which it had chosen the successful tenderer.
When building a motorway, the contracting entity selected the companies for smaller orders of up to 20,000 euros solely on the basis of telephone surveys on prices and delivery conditions.
Examinations of this selection were not possible because the surveys were not documented.
Summary findings
In both countries, the rules governing the examination and evaluation of the offers comply with the requirements of the EU.
However, in the case of details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective rules differ from each other.
In Germany, the procedural process is regulated more strongly than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, in particular for the implementation of the multieye principle and for the protection of tenders.
The same applies to the specifications on the basis of which the adequacy of the prices offered is to be assessed.
In both countries, some of the procurement procedures examined had to be found that significant procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of tenders were not or insufficiently documented.
However, without traceability and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions, possible manipulative interventions are favored.
A particularly serious defect was the handing over of all tenders to third parties without the contracting authority having sufficiently looked through and documented the tenders in advance, thereby protecting them from possible manipulation in further proceedings.
If contracting authorities have tasks performed in the examination and evaluation of tenders by third parties, sufficient precautions and increased control effort are required to counter the increased risk of manipulation.
When assessing the adequacy of the prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the set of tools and did not adequately examine the price structure of the tenders.
In the Czech Republic, complaints were mainly found in the qualification examination and in the application of the evaluation criteria.
Completion of the award procedure
After the tenders have been verified and valued, the award procedure shall be concluded by award of the award or by cancelled the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all tenderers shall be informed in advance of the proposed award decision.
Companies have the option of examining the intended award within 10 days in the case of information by electronic means or by fax or within 15 days for other means of communication and, if necessary, initiating a review procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this information period.
