If a bidder makes a request for review within the information period, the conclusion of a contract is only possible after the final decision in the review procedure.
Companies may also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court in the context of this review procedure.
The review procedure is intended to ensure legal protection for companies and encourage the contracting entity to comply with the procurement law throughout the procurement procedure.
In order to do so, the procedure must be sufficiently documented.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar rules
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and review procedures.
In both countries, the issuing agency has to decide on the award of the award.
However, it must not deviate arbitrarily from the result of a proper examination and evaluation of the offers.
The contracting entity shall award the contract within the announced award period;
also because the tenderers are no longer bound by their tenders after the deadline has expired.
In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and restricted tenders, the contracting entity may not deviate from the content of the tender at the time of conclusion of the contract.
The unsuccessful tenderers shall be informed promptly of the decision to award the award and of the reasons for not taking into account their tenders.
Procurement procedures may be cancelled only under certain conditions, for example if the tender prices are excessive or if the tenders do not meet the requirements of the invitation to tender.
Differing regulations
In the Czech Republic, there is a 10-day or 15-day obligation to provide information and wait before the award of the contract, even in the case of construction services not to be awarded across Europe.
In Germany, these requirements apply only to the area of EU-wide awards.
In the case of other procedures in Germany, tenderers can only be informed of the award decision after the award has been awarded.
In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure should be repealed if only one tender has been received or only one tender could be considered.
In Germany, the contract shall also be awarded in the case of only one valuable tender, provided that the tender complies with the conditions laid down in the tender and is economic.
Significant test results
BRH
In the case of the procurement procedures examined, there were only a few complaints when the procurement procedures were concluded.
In some cases, companies received letters of contract for EU-wide contracts before the expiry of the information deadlines, which may lead to the ineffectiveness of the contract.
In individual cases, commissioned letters also contained content that deviates from the content of the offer, such as changed dates, in accordance with open procedures.
In several cases, contracting entities did not adhere to the award deadlines.
Therefore, in the case of an open procedure, a contrasting entity awarded the second most advantageous tender, since a company with a 50% more favourable tender was no longer prepared to carry out the services at the price originally offered after the expiry of the award period.
NKÚ
In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting party deviated from the tenderer's offer in terms of content in the contract.
In the case of some contracts, for example in the case of road maintenance, the construction of a motorway and a bypass road, the contracting entities concluded the contracts after the expiry of the statutory period.
When awarding works for the refurbishment of former military sites, the contracting party forwarded the notice of the award to all tenderers only after the expiry of the statutory period.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the EU's requirements for the completion of the procurement procedure.
The legal protection of the unsuccessful candidates or tenderers increases the tools for preventing corruption.
The scope of legal protection in Czech procurement law is also extended to awards below the EU thresholds.
In both countries, the deadlines for the award of contracts have been exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
The construction authorities should avoid the identified shortcomings in the completion of their procurement procedures in the future.
Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations
The procurement procedures shall be documented in a comprehensible manner during each stage with regard to the relevant findings and the reasons for each decision.
In the case of EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded shall be disclosed.
The order data is also recorded in EU statistics.
Requirements of EU law and prevention of corruption Documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency bid.
A carefully and promptly prepared documentation enables the procurement decisions to be traceable.
In particular, it also serves to effectively protect tenderers in relation to contracts above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of the prevention of corruption, as the need to substantiate procurement decisions substantially narrows the scope for manipulation.
The notice of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure shall be sent to the Office for Official Publications of the EU within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU, thereby also implementing the transparency requirement.
The contracting entities shall also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the relevant national ministries of the EU Commission.
On this basis, the EU Commission compiles an annual EU statistics to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Regulations of German and Czech procurement law
Same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed EU documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The regulations on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Differing regulations
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts awarded is not only limited to EU-wide procurement, but also covers the other procurement procedures.
The notice period is reduced to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide awards, a publication obligation only exists for limited tenders and for freehand contracts with a value limit of EUR 25,000 or EUR 15,000 excluding VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these limits, as well as in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure receive information on the award of contracts.
