Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two main areas which are essential in the procurement of works by public contracting authorities in the Czech Republic and Germany: the application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Corruption prevention measures are not only aimed at avoiding or at least reducing corruption. They should also avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two Court of Auditors on the application of public procurement rules in both countries and the comparison of these rules reveal similarities and differences which may be helpful for both countries in the further development of their procurement law and its application.
Application of EU procurement rules
Both countries have transposed the EU's requirements for the award of works into national law.
This provides an important common basis in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of works and for taking into account the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the undertakings involved and transparency of procurement procedures.
The construction administrations of both countries have partly compensated these bids very extensively by further administrative regulations.
The Czech Republic has broadly also transferred the requirements for the works to be awarded throughout the EU to its nationally adjustable procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the examinations carried out by the auditors have shown that the construction authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The construction administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the reported complaints when implementing the EU guidelines.
Examinations in the Czech Republic have highlighted above all dangers that affect the profitability of the awards.
For example, incomplete specifications required additional benefits, which were often awarded in breach of legislation. In addition, cost investigations were usually insufficient. Exaggerated qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the case of transport structures.
Corruption prevention
The investigations did not aim to detect cases of corruption
also because the Court of Auditors do not have the appropriate tools for this purpose.
However, the Court of Auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken measures against corruption and manipulation in the procurement of works and how these requirements are applied.
In the prevention of corruption, both countries have set different priorities.
The German regulations foresee largely unlimited competition as well as transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.
The Czech regulations aim above all to increase the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of the prevention of corruption apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of works and are aligned with their specific requirements.
In some cases, the relevant rules define the way in which the bids to prevent corruption must be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In particular, the BRH considers that the priority of the open procedure or the public tender principle is an appropriate instrument to substantially reduce the risk of corruption in the procurement of works. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative intervention.
Risk analyses and adequate controls (especially the multi-eye principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures and various organisational measures are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.
Therefore, the Federal Republic of Germany does not see a fundamental need to change the relevant requirements of the administrations in the procurement of works.
The rules on the prevention of corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in sub-areas have shown shortcomings in the implementation of some guidelines.
The construction authorities should further train their employees on the rules on corruption prevention and raise them even more awareness of this issue.
A substantial part of the complaints related to tasks delegated by the construction authorities to freelancers.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of misuse increases when delegating tasks.
Tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should therefore only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interference.
NKÚ
At government level, the Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption, in which public procurement is the most important component.
The Procurement Act and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The NKÚ audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures as contracting entities assess the profitability of contracts, the calculation of expected prices, the adequacy of qualification requirements, the key evaluation criteria and the nature of assessments and must properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The NKÚ and the BRH assess the implementation of the EU guidelines in principle positively.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU bids of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of works within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and immaterial potential of damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the procurement of works, both auditors see the demand for the construction authorities in their countries to continue and, if necessary, to improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continually examined for vulnerabilities and risks in order to identify the need for action and take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures provide a wider area for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
A greater division of works into lots can also have a favourable effect on offer prices provided that it achieves greater competition with a higher number of tenderers.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for an efficient procurement activity of contracting authorities.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialized construction administrations. In the Czech Republic, however, these tasks — with the exception of transport projects — are carried out by the departments themselves or contractors commissioned by them.
The Court of Auditors of both countries is anxious to develop the relevant findings and, if necessary, bring them to the parliament and government of their country, even after their joint project has been completed.
Both Court of Auditors also believe that the principles of public procurement law and its implementation set out in this report are also of interest at the international level of the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI). The principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and to ensure the economic allocation of works in a well-functioning and fair competition.
